<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-759-132  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 759 132.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Oct 2 1989 v217 n15 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telcos are singing the bargain basement blues. (telephonecompanies seek lower cost fiber optic test equipment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Warr, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Telephone companies want rugged fiber optic network test andmeasurement equipment that is simpler and far less expensive andcomplex than optical time domain reflectometers (OTDRs), which maycost as much as $40,000.andP;  OTDRs were extensively used in theinstallation of long-haul fiber optic cables, but carriers do notwant less-than-$5,000 tools that a crafts person can take down amanhole or up a pole for use in local 'subscriber' loopapplications.andP;  Power meters, cable fault locators using reflectiontechnology, and other new technologies may provide the answer tothe carriers' needs.andP;  OTDRs also currently suffer from a shortdistance 'blind spot' that makes them generally unsuitable forlocal loop applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone SystemsFiber OpticsTest EquipmentTrendsOptical communications.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   US fiber optic test and measurement equipment market, 1986-1995.andO;(graph)Growth of customer markets, 1987-1990. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>